<subSubSection id="49C942EEFF8F3957EBD2C550FD0959C0" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="016C1165FF8F3957EBD2C550FEAA594B" blockId="33.[227,341,611,637]" box="[227,341,611,637]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<heading id="5A24A609FF8F3957EBD2C550FEAA594B" bold="true" box="[227,341,611,637]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF8F3957EBD2C550FEAA594B" bold="true" box="[227,341,611,637]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FF8F3957EBD2C5A0FD0959C0" blockId="33.[226,1438,659,758]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
These small otoliths show a similar outline to what is seen in those of the congrine genera 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF8F3957EE1DC5A0FA61599B" authorityName="Swainson" authorityYear="1838" box="[1324,1438,659,685]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Congridae" genus="Ariosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF8F3957EE1DC5A0FA61599B" box="[1324,1438,659,685]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Ariosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF8F3957EA25C58BFE4959E7" authorityName="Bleeker" authorityYear="1868" box="[276,438,696,721]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Congridae" genus="Heteroconger" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF8F3957EA25C58BFE4959E7" box="[276,438,696,721]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Heteroconger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but otoliths of 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF8F3957E95EC58BFD1E59E4" authorityName="Swainson" authorityYear="1838" box="[623,737,696,722]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Congridae" genus="Ariosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF8F3957E95EC58BFD1E59E4" box="[623,737,696,722]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Ariosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
do not exhibit such a strong convexity of the inner face and considerable thickness at their juvenile stage.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
